<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18420822-2538">
               <interp inst="t18420822-2538" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18420822"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18420822-2538" type="date" value="18420822"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18420822-2538-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2538-18420822 t18420822-2538-offence-1 t18420822-2538-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>2538. <persName id="def1-2538-18420822" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-2538-18420822" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2538-18420822" type="age" value="68"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2538-18420822" type="surname" value="CLEMENTS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2538-18420822" type="given" value="DENNIS"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">DENNIS CLEMENTS</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18420822-2538-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18420822-2538-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="kill"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18420822-2538-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="murder"></interp> for the wilful murder of <persName id="t18420822-name-1787" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1787" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1787" type="surname" value="HOLLOWAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1787" type="given" value="BRIDGET"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420822-2538-offence-1 t18420822-name-1787"></join>Bridget Holloway</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BODKIN</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420822-name-1788" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1788" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1788" type="surname" value="VINCENT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1788" type="given" value="SOPHIA"></interp>SOPHIA VINCENT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Benjamin Vincent, of Smith's-rents, East-lane, Greenwich—I have lived there going on for four years—I knew Bridget Holloway, the deceased—she lived in the next room to me—mine is the front, hers was the back—a partition of wood separates our rooms—you can hear what passes from one room to the other—you can hear persons talk—the prisoner was in the habit of going to the room in which the deceased lived—I thought, at first, they were man and wife—he is a pensioner in the Hospital—on Sunday, the 10th of July, about nine o'clock at night, I was in my own room, and heard the cry of "Murder" coming from the deceased's room several times—I did not hear any other person but her—she continued to cry "Murder" several times, until the cries grew fainter—I went down and told Mrs. Smith, who was at the door—I then went back to my room, and heard no more noise, or cries that night—next day I went into Bridget Holloway's room, about half-past twelve—I brought her up some hot water—I found her sitting on her bed undressed, in her petticoat and shift—she told me she was very bad—she could hardly speak—she was obliged to stop two or three times between the words—she showed me her left side—it was all bruised black and discoloured—she said she should never get over it, for she was sure her ribs were broken—she appeared to be labouring under the impression that she should die—she said the prisoner had done it by constantly knocking her on the side—I saw her again on Tuesday evening, and then no more till after her death—she died on Thursday—about twelve o'clock on Tuesday night I was in my own room, and heard her groans—I never heard her any</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184208220253"></xptr>
               <p>more—she told me, on Tuesday, that she was a great deal worse, and she complained of her left side, that she could not lie—it was the same place she had pointed out to me before—on the Thursday after her death, I saw the prisoner at Dr. Mitchell's, and asked him if she had been worse the night before—he said no, she had been better—I said she could not be better, for she complained of being very bad—he then began to abuse me—I told him he had ill-used her—he denied it—I did not say anything about the cries I had heard, because Mr. Mitchell came in, and it was stopped—he went out.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Did you ever see me drunk, or ill-use her? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have heard you ill-use her several times before—I was never in her room when you and she were there, but I have heard you ill-use her many a time with your tongue—I never saw you strike her.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420822-name-1789" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1789" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1789" type="surname" value="MATTHEWS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1789" type="given" value="SUSAN MARY"></interp>SUSAN MARY MATTHEWS</persName>
                  </hi>. I lived in this house. On Sunday night, the 10th of July, about nine o'clock, I saw the prisoner come out of the deceased's room—she called him an infernal rogue, and said he had <hi rend="italic">done</hi> for her now—he had given her a death-blow—as he passed by the door. he made answer, "You infernal b—h, it serves you right."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Did you hear me say so? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, I did—I saw you go down stairs—my door was open.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner</hi>. God forgive you! I made no answer.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420822-name-1790" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1790" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1790" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1790" type="given" value="SUSAN MART"></interp>SUSAN MART SMITH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Henry Smith, a shoemaker, and live in Smith's-rents, in the room under Bridget Holloway. On Sunday evening, the 10th of July, about eight o'clock, I was going down stairs, and met her on the stairs—she appeared to be as well as usual—the spoke to me—I do not know what age she was—she appeared about seventy—Mrs. Vincent came and told me something; that evening, in consequence of which, I went up into my own room, and heard the deceased crying bitterly, in her own room—I did not see her any more that night—about half-past eight in the morning, I heard her knocking in her room—I went out to see what it was, and then went up into her room—she was just sat down on the bed—she was alone—when she spoke she put her hand to her left side, and it was several seconds before she could speak—she showed me her bruises—I observed bruises on her side—she said she was sure her ribs were broken, and he had given her her death-blow—she had a bruise on each arm, a bruise on her breast, and a slight one on the leg, besides those on the side—I went up about one o'clock, and took her a little broth, thinking it might do her good—she seemed in more agonizing pain than before—she was in the habit of going into the streets with a basket, for the last eight months—she went out that afternoon, between three and four o'clock—I carried her basket down stairs for her—she seemed very bad, and still complained of being very ill, that he had given her her death<lb></lb>blow, and she should never get over it—she returned between six and seven—I saw her next day, Tuesday, between three and four in the after<lb></lb>noon—she appeared to be getting worse—I did not see her on Wednesday—I heard her in her room about half-past twelve at night, groaning very much indeed—on Thursday morning, about half-past seven, the prisoner opened my door, came in, and said, "She is gone; she is gone"—another person said directly, "Is she gone to the Union?"—he said, "No; she is dead, she is dead"—in consequence of that, I went up stairs into the room, and found her dead, but not quite cold—there was a bruise to be seen then on her side as she was lying—the prisoner said, "What do you think will be done in this case?"—I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184208220254"></xptr>
               <p>said I did not know, it would appear very dark against him—he said, "The bruise was done by her daughter, some years ago"—I said "It would have been worn out before this time"—he made no answer to that—we all three then left the room.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Did you see me come down stairs drunk while there, or abuse the woman, or <hi rend="italic">kick up</hi> any noise all the time you had been there? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—I was never up in the room—I have heard that you ill-treated her very much before I went there—I never saw or heard you ill-use her—I never heard any quarrelling.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420822-name-1791" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1791" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1791" type="surname" value="MITCHELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1791" type="given" value="THOMAS OAK"></interp>THOMAS OAK MITCHELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a surgeon, and live at Greenwich. I knew the deceased before this occurred—I was called to see her after her death—the prisoner applied to me to give a certificate of the cause of death—I had attended the woman twelve months prior, for a rheumatic affection—at the time the prisoner called on me he stated that she had been in a very infirm state of health a long time—I left the room, to consult a medical report book—on my return, I found Mrs. Vincent there, and in consequence of hearing the word "ill-treatment" made use of, I refused the certificate—I afterwards, by the order of the Coroner, examined the body externally—it presented appearances of bruises, extending from the left shoulder, over the left side, nearly to the pelvis, and also marks of bruises on the right and left arm—four ribs were fractured, two of which were found penetrating a portion of the left lung, which, in my judgment, was the immediate cause of death—the most prominent symptom was the difficulty of breathing—a blow or a kick would most probably produce such an injury—it must have been very violent—I should say she had been suffering from the injury three or four days.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner</hi>. She had been under him once before with a very bad cough, and was ailing; she took liquor, and has fallen down stairs; it is not the first time I have taken her up stairs, bruised, and complaining of her side. <hi rend="italic">Witness</hi>. I never attended her before with any complaint of that description—she was subject to rheumatic affection in the winter—the body was in other respects perfectly healthy—the fracture of the ribs was the cause of death, by producing inflammation of the lungs—I doubt whether, if it had been seen to in the first instance, that life could have been saved, from the position in which the ribs were, and the lung being lacerated—it might have given her a chance.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420822-name-1792" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1792" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1792" type="surname" value="BERRIDGE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1792" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH BERRIDGE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a surgeon. I assisted Mr. Mitchell in the <hi rend="italic">post mortem</hi> examination—he has correctly stated the appearances of the body—I agree with him entirely in his opinion as to the cause of death.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420822-name-1793" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1793" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1793" type="surname" value="COOLAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1793" type="given" value="JEREMIAH"></interp>JEREMIAH COOLAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. I took the prisoner into cus<lb></lb>tody on this charge, and told him I took him on suspicion of killing a woman—he said he was innocent—in taking him to the station, I asked him How the wounds were inflicted on the body—he said they were caused by falling down stairs.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence</hi>. Some friends from London came to see me, and after dinner we went to a public-house; the deceased drank with us all the afternoon; I went to see my friends off, and then went home; the old woman was pretty well, only had drank too much; I was sitting in my chair, when she took a start, and said, "I want some money;" I looked at her, and said, "I have got none to give you, you have had plenty to drink. without having any more;" she said, "You b—thief, if you don't give it to me I will knock you down;" she took up the hair-broom to give me</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184208220255"></xptr>
               <p>a knock on the head; she said, "I don't expect to live long, and I will leave you in trouble before I go;" I took the broom out of her hand, put it in the corner, and was going out, when she caught hold of my collar, dragged me back, and said, "You want to go out to your wh—s, you must give roe some money;" I said, "Let go;" she would not, but was drag<lb></lb>ging and striking me; I gave her a <hi rend="italic">shove</hi> with one band, and she went back right against the bedstead; she screamed, "Murder!" I said, "Oh, you villain, this is what you wanted, to bring me into trouble;" I went out, and went to the College; I saw her next day, about two o'clock, sit<lb></lb>ting in the street with her basket, but never spoke to her, and on Tuesday morning I saw her in the same place; she shook her head and hand, and said, "You b—thief, I will fetch you in before I go, I know my time is not long;" she went up stairs, and breathed hard; she was a very un<lb></lb>healthy woman; I saw her again that night come out of a public-house; I paid her rent, but never lived with her, only for shame's take; the fol<lb></lb>lowed me from London; I gave her up several times, but she would come after me; I saw her several times on Wednesday; she seemed as well as ever, and I bought her sixpenny worth of cakes to sell next day; when I left her at night she told me to lock the door, and take the key with me, which I did, and went to the College; when I came, about seven o'clock next morning, she was in bed; that frightened roe, and I ran down and told the people that she was gone; they went up, and she had her hands clenched, as if she was in convulsions; I went and told Mr. Mitchell of it, he told me the Jury must sit on her, and I had her laid out.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18420822-2538-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18420822-2538-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18420822-2538-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="manslaughter"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GUILTY</hi> of Manslaughter. Aged 68.—<hi rend="italic">Recommended to</hi> mercy.</rs>—
<rs id="t18420822-2538-punishment-319" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18420822-2538-punishment-319" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
